<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I. INTRODUCTION</TI>
<P>1. The within action arises with respect to the lawyer-client relationship that existed as between Shidan Ashraf (&ldquo;Ashraf&rdquo;), and the Defendants, Gabor Zinner and Zinner Law Office (hereinafter &ldquo;Zinner&rdquo;). This action arises as a result of Zinner's professional negligence, breach of contract and breach of fiduciary duty. The relationship between Ashraf and Zinner commenced when Ashraf approached Zinner in April 2012, seeking assistance regarding his problems with his then-employer, SNC Lavalin (&ldquo;SNC LAVALIN&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. Ashraf was formerly the Chief Engineer of Telecommunications discipline at SNC's Transmission and Distribution Division. Following a sustained and systematic campaign of marginalization and abuse by SNC which was designed to force Ashraf to leave his employment, Ashraf developed severe stress-related illnesses and eventually left his employment with SNC in August of 2011.</P>
<P>3. Ashraf formally retained Zinner to advise him on his legal rights and possibility of pursuing legal recourse against SNC (the &ldquo;Retainer Agreement&rdquo;). Zinner provided a legal opinion that advised framing the claim as a workplace injury rather than as constructive dismissal claim, which was what he had initially advised, because the quantum of award Ashraf could have collected would have greatly exceeded any pay in lieu of notice if the cause of action for constructive dismissal was pursued. Subsequently Zinner filed a Statement of Claim on July 31, 2012, as recognized by the courts as a standalone tort claiming damages for personal injury (the &ldquo;SNC Action&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. As a result of the manner in which Zinner framed the Statement of Claim, SNC filed an Application on September 14, 2012 to strike Ashraf's Statement of Claim in the SNC Action, alleging that Ashraf's claim was statutorily barred by the <EM>Workers' Compensation Act</EM> of Alberta (&ldquo;WCA&rdquo;). This came as a shock to Ashraf as the Defendants had not advised him of the existence of workers' compensation legislation, and its fatal statutory bar on a standalone tort.</P>
<P>5. Ashraf requested Zinner legal advice in terms of moving the action forward but the advice he received after several promises of providing advice soon, eventually came on October 4, 2012, that Ashraf shall discontinue the action should the <EM>WCA</EM> bar apply to the case.</P>
<P>6. Moreover, during the same period, Zinner took a position of disinterest and decided not to take any more proactive steps in moving the case forward without communicating this fact to Ashraf at the time.</P>
<P>7. As a result of the foregoing, Ashraf thereafter terminated the Retainer Agreement on October 9, 2012. However, the damages did not end there. Ashraf was left incapable of handing the SNC Action to another lawyer.</P>
<P>8. SNC's application to strike the SNC Action was heard on February 14, 2013, and the Court granted SNC's application.</P>
<P>9. There were nearly two dozen applications in the SNC Action, including two resulting in a reported decision from the Alberta Court of Appeal, in order to restore Ashraf's action and amend it to include claims for constructive dismissal. Ashraf represented himself at all of them while relying on the services and the legal advice he received from lawyers on project by project basis. His health worsened markedly during this period.</P>
<P>10. The SNC Action was scheduled to proceed to trial in November 2017. However, the lawyer Ashraf hired to prepare for the trail and represent him detected the error in limitations pleadings and advised him of very high risk of limitation arguments at the trial. Moreover, at the 11<SUP>th</SUP> hour she refused to represent the Plaintiff at the trial due to the offer of settlement from SNC. The Plaintiff suffered a series of panic attacks, got very sick, hospitalized and had to stay in bed for almost two weeks. The Plaintiff was unable to procced to trial due to, the high risk of losing the limitation arguments, the fact he was not going to be represented at the trial and his ill health just before the trial and therefore he followed the advice of his lawyer and settled the SNC Action for significantly less than it was worth.</P>
<P>11. Ashraf submits that Zinner is liable for but not limited to the numerous applications and the litigation required to revive the SNC Action all the way from 2012 to November 2017, the resulting shortfall in the SNC Action had the action been started properly, and the aggravation to Ashraf's mental and physical health and all the consequential loses and etc. These losses are direct, foreseeable results of Zinner's failure to provide reasonably competent legal services, along with Zinner essentially giving up on his client while remaining solicitor of record.</P>
<P>12. The parties have agreed to address the issue of damages, including the &ldquo;trial-within-a-trial,&rdquo; after this Court has made a determination with respect to liability.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II. FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Background to the SNC Action</TI>
<P>13. As the result of the systematic campaign of marginalization and abuse by SNC designed to force Ashraf to leave his employment, Ashraf developed severe stress-related illnesses and eventually left his employment with SNC in August of 2011.</P>
<P>14. Ashraf went on short term disability on January 7, 2010, which converted to long term disability in three months later in April 2010. In October 2010, Sun Life Financial of Canada, the disability benefit provider, proposed to Ashraf gradual return to work plan to SNC. On August 2011, Ashraf informed Sun Life and SNC that he was not going to return to work for SNC because his several requests in writings and/or in person between October 2010 and June 2011, for his accommodation and improvement to the toxic work environment remained without any meaningful response.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Solicitor-client relationship between the Parties</TI>
<P>15. In April 2012, Ashraf met Zinner to provide legal services in relation to a potential lawsuit against his employer, SNC-Lavalin (&ldquo;SNC&rdquo;), as a result of the forgoing mistreatment. He received a draft of the retainer date April 26<SUP>th</SUP>, 2012 and paid Zinner a retainer amount of $5,000, on June 26, 2012 when Zinner returned from his holiday.</P>
<P>16. In his first meeting with Zinner, on April 26, 2012, Ashraf was advised that he had a cause of action for constructive dismissal and was assured that based on the facts and evidence presented to Zinner, a viable action could be commenced against SNC. In the second meeting on June 26, 2012, Zinner advised Ashraf he would &ldquo;sue in tort&rdquo; instead which will enable him to collect higher compensations for damages.</P>
<P>17. The only risk specific to the case identified by Zinner to Ashraf at that time was a potential issue with his limitation period, but he informed Ashraf that since he is a person suffering from a disability, he can rely on specific provision of the Alberta Limitations Act and seek suspension of the limitation clock. He did not present any case law to support his legal advice and did not show the high threshold of such pleadings.</P>
<P>18. Zinner wrote an opinion letter on July 12, 2012, expressing opinions against his earlier legal advice provided in the meetings he had with Ashraf in April and June 2012. Ashraf met with Zinner on the same date of July 12, 2012 and enquired about Zinner's change of mind. Ashraf also inquired as to why a tort claim raised by Zinner earlier was not discussed in his letter if he was advising against the cause of action for constructive dismissal. Also, Ashraf told Zinner that there are several medical documents he had given him on June 26, 2012 that commented on the facts that Ashraf's physical and psychological illnesses were caused by the stress due to the abusive conduct of his employer and the toxic work environment.</P>
<P>19. Zinner told Ashraf in the same meeting to stay and he will revise his letter. Ashraf was not feeling well and had to leave but Zinner promised to send a revised letter.</P>
<P>20. On July 16, 2012, Zinner sent a revised letter that included the cause of action in tort in addition to constructive dismissal with detailed calculations of the possible monetary value of the claim. Upon its receipt, Ashraf noticed the medical letters were not included and other incorrect statements were included, such as a statement that Ashraf wanted to proceed with litigation for the sake of making a statement even if he was going to be unsuccessful in the lawsuit.</P>
<P>21. These facts were brought to attention of Zinner by Ashraf, and despite Ashraf's preference that Zinner formulate his own understanding of the case, his opinion and pleadings, Zinner asked him to write his comments in the body of his July 16, 2012 opinion letter using the tracking feature of MS Word file.</P>
<P>22. Eventually Zinner sent back another draft of the opinion letter dated July 19, 2012. In the letter he largely copied and pasted Ashraf's language word for word, rather than analyzing the points added from a legal perspective. He also took out the cause of action in constructive dismissal and calculations for its damages from his opinion, confirming he was suing in tort only. This letter represented Zinner legal advice given in person to person meetings, which put Ashraf's mind somewhat at ease that Zinner had not missed or forgotten anything he had told Ashraf in person; however, it took much rework to synchronize Zinner's legal advice in person to what he had written in his opinion.</P>
<P>23. Subsequently, Zinner sent Ashraf a draft of the Statement of Claim which conformed with his July 19, 2012 opinion letter in which he did not allege constructive dismissal nor make any claims for damages arising from constructive dismissal such as pay in lieu of notice.</P>
<P>24. Ashraf reminded Zinner that some facts which he had told Ashraf he would have included in the claim were not there. Zinner asked Ashraf to write down the missing facts for Zinner's review, which Ashraf did.</P>
<P>25. The final draft was filed on July 31, 2012. It contained about three pages which included Ashraf's word for word feedback, which were intended for Zinner's sole use and consideration in adding properly drafted legal language to the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>26. Subsequent to the filing of the Statement of Claim, upon receipt of Zinner invoices, Ashraf met with Zinner on August 15, 2012 and expressed his frustration about the cost of the legal services to date, which had been higher than expected due to much reworks and inefficiencies in preparing the opinion and Statement of Claim. Reasonable number of hours were discussed based on earlier information given to Ashraf by Zinner for the work which was done.</P>
<P>27. Ashraf continued in the same meeting by saying that, in order to instill higher degree of accountability, he would only continue with Zinner if he agreed to the proposed revised semi-contingency payment arrangement, which was presented by Ashraf to Zinner.</P>
<P>28. Zinner apologized for the inefficiencies of his operation, committed to review the proposed payment scheme and get back to Ashraf in few days. At the within trial, Zinner admitted he never told Ashraf at the time he had not understood the proposed new terms of payment.</P>
<P>29. Zinner informed Ashraf on September 6, 2012, that he had just noticed a fax received from SNC three weeks earlier on August 17, 2012 asking for additional time to file a defense. Ashraf and Zinner met on the same date and Ashraf agreed with extension of time beyond the limitation period for the Defendant to respond. At the meeting Zinner also requested for payment to &ldquo;keep the lights on&rdquo;. Ashraf offered to pay according to the hours discussed on August 15, 2012, meeting which were recorded in their August 20 emails. Ashraf's calculations came to $3,500.00 while Zinner recalculated hours using the correct rate and came to an amount of $3,675.00. He asked Ashraf for that amount which Ashraf paid him upon Zinner agreeing that this sum was full payment for Zinner's work to date.</P>
<P>30. Zinner noted SNC in default on or around September 20, 2012, for being late by about 3 days in filing a response. But in fact, SNC lawyers had faxed their response to Zinner on time but again he had missed seeing the fax on time but only came to his attention after noting SNC in default.</P>
<P>31. On September 14, 2012, SNC had already filed an Application to strike Ashraf's Statement of Claim in the SNC Action, alleging that Ashraf's claim was statutorily barred by the Workers' Compensation Act of Alberta (&ldquo;WCA&rdquo;). This came as a shock to Ashraf as the Defendants had not advised him of the existence of workers' compensation legislation, and its fatal statutory baron a standalone tort or any other cause of action.</P>
<P>32. Ashraf requested legal advice in terms of moving the action forward but the advice he received after several promises of providing advice soon, eventually came on October 4, 2012, that Ashraf shall discontinue the action should the WCA bar apply to the case.</P>
<P>33. Moreover, during the same period, Zinner took a position of disinterest and decided not to take any more proactive steps in moving the case forward without communicating this fact to Ashraf at the time.</P>
<P>34. In the time period intervening between being notified of the WCA defense and being terminated, Zinner never advised Ashraf that he could amend his Statement of Claim to include a cause of action not barred under the WCA. Zinner never informed Ashraf at the time, of his disinterest to continue acting for Ashraf, or his intention in not providing proactive service which is despite his statement before the taxation officer in January 2013 and later on during the cross examination when he said he was &ldquo;conflicted&rdquo; about whether he wanted to continue acting for such a &ldquo;high-maintenance&rdquo; client, and as such, &ldquo;didn't take any more proactive steps on behalf of Mr. Ashraf&rdquo; until he was terminated. Transcript of Gabor Ivan Zinner, July 23, 2015, p 116, ll 6&ndash;23, is in reference.</P>
<P>35. As a result of the foregoing, Ashraf thereafter terminated the Retainer Agreement on October 9, 2012. Upon Zinner's termination, he refused to pay Ashraf back the retainer funds which were kept as a float and stated he had never agreed the amount received was in full satisfaction of his invoices. Prior to his termination from September 6 on which he received payment to October 9, 2012, Zinner neither followed up with Ashraf for what he later claimed Ashraf owed him nor sent any statements showing Ashraf is in arrears.</P>
<P>36. However, the damages did not end there. Ashraf was left with a summary judgement Application from SNC on his hands, he was still in shock of how Zinner could have betrayed his trust and also financially incapable of handing the SNC Action for representation to another lawyer.</P>
<P>37. Ashraf did seek and received legal advice subsequent to Zinner's termination and prior to the foregoing SJ application hearing that he should amend his Statement of Claim to include a claim for constructive dismissal. He was told that he would have to ask for the leave of the Court to do so when he appeared before Master Laycock.</P>
<P>38. Mr. Ashraf was not told that he could have amended without leave, given that no Statement of Defense was filed, and did not find this out until he appeared before Justice Mahoney on appeal from Master Laycock's decision striking his claim. Ashraf did in fact seek leave from Master Laycock to amend his claim and this request was denied.</P>
<P>39. SNC's application to strike the SNC Action was heard on February 14, 2013, and the Court granted SNC's application.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Procedural steps taken to salvage the SNC Action following the Defendant's breaches</TI>
<P>40. There were nearly two dozen applications in the SNC Action to restore the SNC Action and amend it to include constructive dismissal, including two resulting in reported decisions from the Alberta Court of Appeal. Ashraf represented himself at all of them while relying on the services and the legal advice he received from lawyers on project by project basis. His health worsened markedly during this period.</P>
<P>41. The restored SNC Action was scheduled to proceed to trial in November 2017. However, based on legal advice he received from his lawyer, he settled the SNC Action for significantly less than it was worth all evidence of which were presented at the trial.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III: ISSUES</TI>
<P>The Plaintiff's position may be summarized as follows:
<P1>I The Defendants equally liable regardless of professional incorporation, employee status and purported limitation of liability;</P1>
<P1>II The Defendants breach their tortious and contractual duty of care;</P1>
<P1>III The Plaintiff suffered damages caused by the Defendant's breaches of its tortious and contractual duties;</P1>
<P1>IV The Defendant's breach the fiduciary duty owed to the Plaintiff;</P1>
<P1>V The Plaintiff suffered damages caused by the Defendant's breaches of fiduciary duties;</P1></P>
<P>The parties have agreed to address the issues of remedies and damages after this Court has made a determination regarding liability.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV. ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>IV - I.</N><TI>The Defendants are equally liable regardless of professional incorporation, employee status and purported limitation of liability</TI>
<P>42. Zinner's personal liability is not affected by the fact that he operates as a professional corporation:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>133.</N><TI>Liability of shareholders and employees</TI><SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>The liability of any person in carrying on the practice of a barrister and solicitor is not affected by the fact that the practice of a barrister and solicitor is carried on by that person as an employee and on behalf of a professional corporation.</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Legal Profession Act, RSA 2000, c L-8, section 133(2)</EM> [TAB 2]</P1></P>
<P>43. The Retainer Agreement purports to limit the Zinner's liability to the amount of the fees paid. This provision is void pursuant to Rule 10.6(1)(a) of the <EM>Alberta Rules of Court</EM>:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>10.6</N><TI>Void provisions</TI><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>In a retainer agreement or otherwise, a provision is void if the provision
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>purports to relieve a lawyer from liability for negligence or any other liability which the lawyer might be subject as a lawyer, [...]</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Alberta Rules of Court, AR 124/2010 as amended</EM> [TAB 3]</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>IV - II.</N><TI>The Defendants breached their tortious and contractual duty of care</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>A &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>Zinner owed a duty to the Plaintiff to perform his duties to the standard of a reasonably prudent lawyer</EM></TI>
<P>44. A lawyer's duty of care applies to any act or omission in the performance of the services provided.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central &amp; Eastern Trust Co v Rafuse</SOC><CITE>[1986] 2 SCR 147</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1986] SCJ No 52</CITE><PARANUM>61</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>45. The duty of care a lawyer owes his client in contract arises from the terms, both express and implied of any retainer agreement between them.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Strother v. 3464920 Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2007] 2 SCR 177</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2007 SCC 24</CITE><PARANUM>134</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, [TAB 34]</P1></P>
<P>46. The duty of care a lawyer owes his client in tort arises as a result of the relationship between solicitor and client.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central Trust v Rafuse</SOC></CASEREF>, supra at para. 57 [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>47. Zinner's liability is concurrently in tort and contract. The duty of care, and thus an action for a breach of that duty, arises concurrently in tort and contract.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central Trust v Rafuse</SOC></CASEREF>, supra, at para. 58 [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>48. Unless special terms in the retainer agreement limit or expand the duty of care, the duty is the same in both contact and tort.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central Trust v Rafuse</SOC></CASEREF>,, <EM>supra</EM>, para. 69, [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>49. One requirement of professional competence is that a solicitor &ldquo;must have a sufficient knowledge of the fundamental issues or principles of law applicable to the particular work he has undertaken to enable him to perceive the need to ascertain the law on relevant points&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central Trust v Rafuse</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, para. 67-68, [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>50. A lawyer is required to bring reasonable care, skill and knowledge to the performance of the professional services that the lawyer has undertaken for the client. The standard of care is that of the reasonably or ordinarily competent or prudent lawyer and that solicitor is required to &ldquo;bring reasonable care, skill and knowledge to the performance of the professional service which he has undertaken. Absent special contractual terms, the duties and standards set by contract and tort are the same.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>623445 Alberta Ltd v The Partnership of Jackie Handerek &amp; Forester and Shawn D Hagen</SOC><CITE>2018 ABQB 86</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Handerek</EM>] at paras 63&ndash;65 [TAB 6]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Central &amp; Eastern Trust Co v Rafuse</SOC><CITE>[1986] 2 SCR 147</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1986] SCJ No 52</CITE><PARANUM>66</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 4]</P1></P>
<P>51. Moreover, the retainer between Ashraf and Zinner contained no limitations on the standard or duty of care owed by Zinner. Therefore, the applicable standard is that of an ordinary, reasonably competent litigator.</P>
<P>52. Zinner's incorrect and faulty legal advice was not a mere error of judgment. It was not a decision that was unwise in hindsight. Rather, Zinner's assessment of the merits of the SNC Action was incorrect because he did not exercise the knowledge of a reasonably competent lawyer....
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Adeshina v Litwiniuk &amp; Co</SOC><CITE>2010 ABQB 80</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>[Adeshina]</EM> at para 112 [TAB 7]</P1></P>
<P>53. This Court recently summarized the standard of care with respect to a lawyer's competence, including the lawyer's duty to recognize his own strengths and weaknesses....
<P1><EM>Handerek</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 67 [TAB 6]</P1></P>
<P>54. This Court has previously outlined this Defendant's obligations as a member of the legal profession under the Law Society of Alberta's <EM>Code of Professional Conduct</EM> (&ldquo;Code of Conduct&rdquo;). ...
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Mintoft v Becker, Bradley, Zinner et al</SOC><CITE>2011 ABQB 433</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 8]</P1></P>
<P>55. Although this Court is not bound by the Code of Conduct, it serves as <EM>&ldquo;an expression of a professional standard in a code of ethics&rdquo;</EM> and <EM>&ldquo;should be considered an important statement of public policy.&rdquo;</EM> The Code of Conduct is of importance in determining the nature and extent of duties flowing from the solicitor-client relationship.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>MacDonald Estate v Martin</SOC><CITE>[1990] 3 SCR 1235</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1990] SG No 40</CITE><PARANUM>21</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 9]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cunningham v Lilies</SOC><CITE>2010 SCC 10</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 10]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Perez v Galambos</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 48</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 11]</P1></P>
<P>56. In particular, Rule 3.1-1 fleshes out what it means for a lawyer to be &ldquo;competent&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P><EM>3.1-1 &ldquo;competent lawyer&rdquo; means a lawyer who has and applies relevant knowledge, skills and attributes in a manner appropriate to each matter undertaken on behalf of a client and the nature and terms of the lawyer's engagement, including</EM>:</P>
<P><EM>(a)</EM><BOLD><EM>knowing general legal principles and procedures and the substantive law and procedure for the areas of law in which the lawyer practises</EM>;</BOLD></P>
<P><EM>(b) investigating facts</EM>, <BOLD><EM>identifying issues</EM></BOLD>, <EM>ascertaining client objectives, considering possible options and developing and advising the client on appropriate courses of action</EM>;</P>
<P><EM>(c) implementing as each matter requires, the chosen course of action through the application of appropriate skills, including</EM>:
<P1><EM>(i)</EM><BOLD><EM>legal research</EM></BOLD>;</P1></P>
<P><EM>(d)</EM><BOLD><EM>communicating with the client at all relevant stages of a matter in a timely and effective manner;</EM></BOLD></P>
<P><EM>(h)</EM><BOLD><EM>recognizing limitations in one's ability to handle a matter or some aspect of it</EM></BOLD><EM>and taking steps accordingly to ensure the client is appropriately served</EM>;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Code of Conduct, Law Society of Alberta</EM>, [TAB 12]</P1></P>
<P>57. Further, the Commentary to that Rule enumerates in its para 3, factors relevant to determining whether the lawyer employed the requisite degree of knowledge and skill in a particular matter, including:
<P1><EM>a. The complexity and specialized nature of the matter</EM>;</P1>
<P1><EM>b. The lawyer's general experience</EM>;</P1>
<P1><EM>c. The lawyer's training and experience in the field</EM>;</P1>
<P1><EM>d. The preparation and study the lawyer is able to give the matter; and</EM></P1>
<P1><EM>e. Whether it is appropriate or feasible to refer the matter to, or associate or consult with, a lawyer of established competence in the field in question</EM>.</P1>
<P1><EM>Code of Conduct, Rule 3.1-1 Commt'y</EM> at para 3 [TAB 12]</P1></P>
<P>58. As noted above, Zinner's professional responsibility and his civil liability are two separate matters. However, the Code of Conduct provides evidence of &ldquo;customary norms&rdquo; that &ldquo;may be seen as implied terms of the retainer&rdquo; and &ldquo;part of the standard of care to be expected of a prudent practitioner.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Adeshina</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at paras 116-117 [TAB 7]</P1></P>
<P>59. Indeed, Zinner's Retainer Agreement in Exhibit D.4 of the Plaintiff's Book of Exhibits, expressly named in its para 5, the identification of issues and &ldquo;thoroughness&rdquo; as a key characteristic of the solicitor-client relationship, But Zinner failed to deliver according to the terms of his retainer...
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>5.</N><TI>THE FIRM'S APPROACH</TI>
<P>We try to identify:</P>
<P>a) what you see as the issues,</P>
<P>b) what your concerns are,</P>
<P>c) what your expectations are.</P>
<P>To do this, thoroughness is very important. All the facts must be assessed. Issues must be identified, and once identified must be pursued with superior preparation and effort. Researchers assist in depth. This leads to superior results.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>B &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>Zinner's substandard legal services fell below the requisite standard of care</EM></TI>
<P>60. The Plaintiff respectfully states that the Defendants breached their tortious and contractual duties of care with respect to at least four main areas:
<P1>a. failing to identify the applicable limitation period to the constructive dismissal claim;</P1>
<P1>b. failing to detect the <EM>WCA</EM> issue;</P1>
<P1>c. failing to plead the only meritorious cause of action, that is, constructive dismissal; and seek damages for stress arising from the manner of dismissal;</P1>
<P1>d. failing to address those errors by properly advising Ashraf of his procedural options in a timely manner or at all.</P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>Zinner did not identify the correct limitation period for the constructive dismissal claim</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>61. In carrying out his retainer, Zinner advised Ashraf that his treatment by the management of SNC, such as including but not limited to two unjustified demotions, virtual suspension, marginalization, humiliation, unjustified disciplinary actions with false accusations, reprimands, warnings, negative performance reviews, freezing salary and etc. and etc. as part of systematic abusive campaign to force him out of employment was one to give rise to a claim for constructive dismissal, were it not barred by the Limitations Act. He also told Ashraf that he would but frame the action in another branch of law as a tort instead of constructive dismissal to be able to claim higher compensation. However, in relation to a cause of action for constructive dismissal, Zinner's limitation opinion appeared to have been based on Zinner's belief that:</P>
<P>62. Limitations periods under the Limitations Act, RSA 2000 c. L-12, as amended, begin when an injured person becomes aware of their injuries;
<P1>a. Ashraf became aware of his injuries on the day he went on medical leave from work (January 7, 2010); and</P1>
<P1>b. This limitation period applied to constructive dismissal.</P1>
<P1>c. Ashraf became aware that the injuries warrant bringing an action;</P1>
<P1>d. This limitation period applied to constructive dismissal.</P1></P>
<P>63. Instead, the plain wording of section 3(l)(a) and (b) of the <BOLD><EM>Limitations Act</EM></BOLD> is ...
<P1>[TAB 13]</P1></P>
<P>64. Ashraf went to Zinner to find out whether or not he had grounds to complain about abusive conducts of his employer which forced him out of employment. Constructive dismissal was the &ldquo;<BOLD>essential character</BOLD>&rdquo; of his complaints for seeking justice. But even on a tort standard, his cause of action would not have &ldquo;crystallized&rdquo; until he first spoke with Zinner on April 26, 2012.</P>
<P>65. In addition to assuming that a limitation period arises when injuries are sustained, and not when a claimant first learns that the injuries might warrant a proceeding, Zinner appears also to have determined that the &ldquo;injury&rdquo; suffered by Ashraf which would have given rise to the claim for constructive dismissal was having to go on disability on or around January 7, 2010. This was wrong, as the &ldquo;injury&rdquo; suffered in a claim for constructive dismissal arose from the manner of constructive dismissal in Ashraf's employment which ended in or about August 2011, after the employer shown their intention not to be bound by the terms of contract, implied or otherwise, which had made continued employment intolerable for Ashraf.</P>
<P>66. In other words, the injuries or loss of earning capacity and thereby the wage loss must have been among the heads of damages arising from the manner of constructive dismissal and not a standalone tort.</P>
<P>67. Correspondence between Ashraf and his employer between October 2010 and June 2011, in Plaintiff's Exhibits D8.1 to D8.4 (snc), D.54, are clear evidence of Ashraf's attempt to mitigate his losses by showing willingness, subject to his physician's supervision and approval, to undertake a gradual return to work plan as proposed by Sun Life, provided SNC would attend to the issues which had forced him out of work in the first place by way of causing him harm.</P>
<P>68. If for nothing else this lack of response of SNC and their unwillingness to accommodate Ashraf was a worthwhile test which proved the emptiness of SNC promises and lip service with no substance.</P>
<P>69. Ashraf requested SNC Lavalin, in good faith for meaningful accommodation of a gradual return to work plan, which fulfilled his legal duty to mitigate his losses as he had done before. However, when his requests remained without response and resolutions, his employment ended. It is submitted that it was at that point, and not at any earlier time, that Ashraf's cause of action for constructive dismissal fully &ldquo;crystallized&rdquo; and the limitation period began to run.</P>
<P>70. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mifsud v. MacMillan Bathurst Inc</SOC><CITE>1989 CanLII 260</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the Honourable courts stated the following with respect to the legal duty of an employee to mitigate his losses....
<P1>Page 12, Para 6, [TAB 57]</P1></P>
<P>71. However, Zinner assumed (incorrectly) that the limitation period on a claim for constructive dismissal had arisen when Ashraf went on disability leave, Zinner framed the Statement of Claim as an action for personal injuries at work, rather than a claim for constructive dismissal. He intentionally did not plead constructive dismissal as recorded in the cross examination, (Transcript July 23, 2015, page 113, lines 16-17) he did not even plead breach of employment contract as per his own testimonies under oath, telling Ashraf at the time that he would recover significantly more damages in the alternatives cause of action for a tort.</P>
<P>72. Whereas the cause of action in its essential character and <UNDER>true</UNDER> legal framework of the pleadings was one for constructive dismissal and its amendment later on to constructive dismissal was not an &ldquo;<BOLD>afterthought solution</BOLD>&rdquo;.</P>
<P>73. Ashraf submits that, particularly in light of Zinner's self-proclaimed expertise in employment law, Zinner breached the standard of care by failing to determine the correct limitation date of Ashraf's constructive dismissal claim.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>Zinner did not identify the WCA bar to the SNC Action</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>74. It is submitted that, at the time Zinner was acting for Ashraf, he crafted at least two bars to the claim as Zinner was framing it.</P>
<P>75. <BOLD>First,</BOLD> the claim would be (and was) barred by operation of sections 1(1)(a), 14(1), 21, of the <EM>Workers Compensation Act</EM>, RSA 2000 c. W-15, as amended, (herein after &ldquo;WCA&rdquo;) states, in material part...
<P1><EM>Workers Compensation Act</EM>, RSA 2000 c. W-15, [TAB 14]</P1></P>
<P>76. In the Province of Alberta, the <EM>WCA</EM> bar applies according to its <EM>Principles of WCA, System 3</EM>, which is in [TAB 15], to work-related injuries where and when the <UNDER>&ldquo;activities causing the injury are part of the employer's normal insured activities of employment, based on a reasonable person test, and operate to displace any tort remedy for that injury&rdquo;.</UNDER> The bar therefore applies to causes of actions when dismissal and/or breach of employment contract law are not pled and whether or not the injured employee receive disability benefits from WCA. Wrongful constructive dismissal and particularly the manner in which it is conducted is a breach in employment law to which the employer's corporation is a party and is not as part of normal insured activities of employment.
<P1><EM>Principles of WCA, System 3</EM>, which is in [TAB 15]</P1></P>
<P>77. The following case law show that the events and transaction in the SNC case would have not qualified for the definition &ldquo;accident&rdquo;. Also the WCA bar applies to &ldquo;accident&rdquo;, whether disability benefits are paid out or not by WCA. In <CASEREF><SOC>Medicine Hat (City) v. Wilson</SOC></CASEREF> (City Buses), the injuries of employees satisfied <EM>WCA's</EM> requirements for definition of accident, but no compensations were paid out to the employees due to inadequate evidence between cause and effect. Subsequently a civil action started against the employer which was dismissed by the court (AC of Alberta) because the WCA bar applied even when the alleged injured employee did not receive disability benefits because injuries were part of normal insured activities of employment and &ldquo;accident&rdquo;. In other words, WCA jurisdiction and its bar are based on satisfying the requirement for definition of &ldquo;accident&rdquo; and not whether such accidents warrant compensations.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Medicine Hat (City) v. Wilson (City Buses)</SOC></CASEREF> [TAB 16]</P1></P>
<P>78. What happened to Ashraf was not &ldquo;<EM>accident</EM>&rdquo; because it was not &ldquo;<EM>as part of normal insured activities of employment</EM>&rdquo;, the conduct of the management &ldquo;<EM>was not inherent hazard of employment</EM>&rdquo;, but the events and transactions that transpired were in violation of employment law, in breach of the duty of good faith and duty of care in the manner his employer was trying to get rid of him by forcing him to resign or have him terminated. Based on definition of accident provided by the <EM>WCA legislation</EM>, Table 1, in [TAB 16], sets down the qualifying criteria for &ldquo;accident&rdquo;, and briefly and clearly compare and differentiate the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf v. SNC</SOC></CASEREF> as compared with <CASEREF><SOC>Medicine Hat (City) v. Wilson</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>79. Zinner admitted, at one point during questioning (Transcript P7 lines 40-41 and P8 lines 34-35, in Plaintiff Exhibit D.48) that at the time of drafting the statement of claim he was aware of the <EM>WCA</EM> bar to a personal injury claim created by the <EM>Workers Compensation Act</EM>. However, he later made a statement that he became aware of the <EM>WCA</EM> bar when brought to his attention by the opposing Application of SNC. However, if that is truly the case, he took no steps to make himself aware of this possible bar while drafting the St of Claim.</P>
<P>80. It is submitted that Zinner was aware of this bar and he derailed the action by intentionally, according to himself, not alleging constructive dismissal, not pleading breach of contract, not claiming damages born out of constructive dismissal and only claiming loud and clear a standalone tort of injuries and damages accordingly to the exclusion of damages for constructive dismissal. Otherwise, he should have conducted research or at least reviewed the <EM>WCA Act</EM>, and authorities on constructive dismissal and cases to make certain the claim he was making was valid in law.</P>
<P>81. The Defendant in the within Zinner Action attempted in the course of this trial to misrepresent the facts surrounding Ashraf's complaint as Ashraf having gone to Zinner to seek legal advice about his sickness/injuries and therefore Zinner started a standalone tort for injuries! This is incorrect. The &ldquo;<BOLD>essential character</BOLD>&rdquo; of Ashraf's complaints was loss of employment and/or his constructive dismissal and the manner of his dismissal in abusive conduct of the management team of his employer, the way he was treated under a systematic abusive campaign and series of acts to marginalize, humiliate and frustrate him to the point he would have resigned and left, or the corporation crafted enough evidence to have him terminated. The damages Ashraf incurred as the result of this manner of employer's conducts were obviously discussed with Zinner but it was made very clear at the time when Ashraf had not even heard the legal terminology of constructive or wrongful dismissal that he had been subjected by his employer's management team to uncivilized, fraudulent, deceptive acts as the result of which manner he had lost his health and his job. So those were the discussions Ashraf and Zinner had when Zinner was formulating his opinion. The cause of action for constructive dismissal was not an <BOLD>afterthought</BOLD> solution to revive his action when faced with the WCA defense. This mischaracterization due to Zinner's professional negligence and breaches is <BOLD><UNDER>the stain and stigma</UNDER></BOLD> from which the action suffered to its end and disallowed majority of the claims to advance to trial.</P>
<P>82. The initial advice of Zinner about allegation of constructive dismissal is a clear evidence which he replaced with a Tort of injuries in the guise of being able to receive higher compensations for Ashraf. Likewise the email of Zinner which is in Plaintiff's Exhibit D.62, supports this fact when Zinner sent to Ashraf a statement by one of Justices of the Supreme Court of Canada, Justice Dickson, who articulated the value of employment as a fundamental contributory element in socially and materially prosperous societies, showing as a matter of assurance that my complaint will be determined to have merits by law depending on the evidence that will be produced.
<P1>[TAB 51]</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>Zinner did not plead the only meritorious cause of action, that is. constructive dismissal</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>83. It is submitted that Zinner's failure to plead the only meritorious cause of action, constructive dismissal, fell below the requisite standard of care.</P>
<P>84. Zinner suggested at Questioning (Transcript July 23, 2015, p 100, II 14-20) that constructive dismissal was in fact sufficiently pled, and that the allegation of constructive dismissal was &ldquo;implied and it is understood, and it should be by any court.&rdquo;</P>
<P>85. The courts did not meet Zinner's expectation that they &ldquo;should&rdquo; discern an implicit plea of constructive dismissal. Master Laycock did not detect such a plea by stating, &ldquo;<EM>Ashraf's employment has not been terminated by the defendant</EM>, <BOLD><EM>nor has Ashraf sued for constructive dismissal as a result of the alleged conduct&rdquo;</EM></BOLD>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf v SNC Lavalin ATP Inc</SOC><CITE>2013 ABQB 143</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 28]</P1></P>
<P>86. Nor did Justice Mahoney detect this ostensibly implicit plea of constructive dismissal:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[...] Mr. Ashraf pleads that he suffered physical injuries, including carpal tunnel syndrome and arthritis in his hands and feet, development of peripheral neuropathy, lupus and swelling on his scrotum. He also pleads he suffered from stress, humiliation and distress. Mr. Ashraf seeks damages for the difference between the long-term disability benefits he receives, and his expected salary and benefits had he remained working at SNC, including annual increases, from January 7, 2010 to September 1, 2022, when he reaches 65 years of age. SNC did not terminate Mr. Ashraf</EM>, <BOLD><EM>and Mr. Ashraf does not claim constructive dismissal in the Statement of Claim, as filed</EM></BOLD>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf v SNC Lavalin ATP Inc</SOC><CITE>2013 ABQB 688</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 29]</P1></P>
<P>87. In fact, the Court of Appeal held that the SNC Action did not take on the constructive dismissal &ldquo;dimension&rdquo; until the Statement of Claim was amended to expressly plead it:
<QUOTE><P><EM>We take no issue with the chambers judge's decision to allow the amendment to add a claim for constructive dismissal. However</EM>, <BOLD><EM>with that amendment the dispute took on a new dimension</EM></BOLD>. <EM>Although the appellant relies on essentially the same facts, his claim</EM><BOLD><EM>now alleges</EM></BOLD><EM>that workplace harassment</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Work force harassment and bullying pled was by management representing the corporation as a party to the contract.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE><EM>and bullying, tolerated by his employer, marginalized him, caused him stress and physical harm, and eventually compelled him to leave his employment. This, says the appellant, amounted to constructive dismissal</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf v SNC Lavalin ATP Inc</SOC><CITE>2015 ABCA 78</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 18]</P1></P>
<P>88. Therefore, it is respectfully submitted that Zinner did not, in fact, sufficiently plead constructive dismissal.</P>
<P>89. <BOLD>The second</BOLD> bar in operation at the time as Zinner crafted it, was that the limitation period on personal injuries which <UNDER>arguably</UNDER>, arose when Ashraf became disabled, on or about January 7 of 2010.</P>
<P>90. In short, neither the plain wordings of the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> was understood nor what constitute the trigger of limitation clock in constructive dismissal, he did not advise Ashraf about <UNDER>the existence of high risks and high threshold</UNDER> of pleading disability in limitation arguments, nor did he take any steps at all to have familiarized himself with these extremely basic aspects of procedural law.</P>
<P>91. As noted in Handerek, &ldquo;As for knowledge, a lawyer should know the elementary or fundamental principles of the area in which he or she is providing services, should be able to recognize topics requiring further legal research, and should be able to ascertain the applicable legal rules. A lawyer should be able to perceive legal issues and to assess the strengths and weaknesses of proposed courses of action in light of those issues. A lawyer should recognize his or her limitations and take steps to remedy those limitations to ensure that he or she provides competent service&rdquo;.</P>
<P>92. Limitation periods, the measure of damages, and how and when a cause of action arises, as well as the situations in which an action for personal injuries are barred are &ldquo;<EM>elementary or fundamental principles&rdquo;</EM> as a litigator, even one not claiming to be experienced in employment law, should know.</P>
<P>93. Instead, Zinner told Ashraf that he had an Action for constructive dismissal, but he is late and has passed the deadline as required by the <EM>limitation Act</EM>. Then he told Ashraf, &ldquo;the good news is for people of disability the limitation requirement is suspended&rdquo; allowing the action to proceed unimpeded as long as disability is pled. He treated the matter as a very simple straight forward argument despite the high threshold for such pleading. He then told Ashraf, in any event, constructive dismissal would only provide him with compensation for up to three to six months' salary in lieu of notice according to a law in Alberta (which really does not exist). He advised that he was instead going to file a claim for lost income in &ldquo;tort&rdquo; which should have compensated Ashraf about $5 million in lost wages.</P>
<P>94. Later in his invoices and at the questioning, Zinner stated to have advised Ashraf that he had a concurrent claim in tort and contract which he never told Ashraf at the time. But then such concurrency is the precise prerequisites for <EM>WCA</EM> jurisdictions if dismissal and breach of employment law is not alleged.</P>
<P>95. It is submitted that Zinner knew Ashraf had claims due to tortious conduct of his employer, he should have drafted the Statement of Claim accordingly clearly pleading dismissal in breaches of employment contract law by the corporation and claimed damages arising from the manner thereof and not leave the essential perimeter of constructive dismissal such as dismissal, end of employment, damages in lieu of notice and etc. not pleaded and open for guess work interpretation of the Defendant and the courts which would have naturally free fall jump into <EM>WCA's</EM> jurisdiction.</P>
<P>96. Zinner stated at this trial he had a lingering fear if he had alleged constructive dismissal in the claim, SNC would in retaliation interfered with Ashraf' disability benefits he receive from SunLife. On the other hand, he confirmed under oath his expectation in filing his statement of claim was that the court would have recognized and legitimized the silent cause of action for constructive dismissal for it to continue the litigation. The case would have at any rate been pursued in litigation for a constructive dismissal suit action against SNC whether Zinner alleged constructive dismissal directly in the Statement of claim or the court decreed a cause of action of constructive dismissal. In either case it would have made no difference if SNC was able and could have taken retaliatory steps to interfere with Ashraf disability benefits. When Zinner was confronted with this fact at the trial, he admitted that this fear was &ldquo;futile&rdquo; and meaningless. It is respectfully submitted this is an empty theory, a childish excuse to hide his intention to derail the action but also created <BOLD>the stigma</BOLD> that the <BOLD>essential character</BOLD> the case was injuries at work which disentitled Ashraf from making such claims arising from the manner of his dismissal.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI><UNDER><EM>Zinner did not advise Ashraf that he could amend his Statement of Claim</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>97. It is submitted that, after receiving correspondence from counsel for SNC advising that they would be relying upon the statutory bar in the WCA, Zinner had a duty to advise Ashraf of his legal options. It is specifically submitted that Zinner breached the duties he owed to Ashraf by failing to advise Ashraf that he could amend his Statement of Claim in response to the position taken by SNC.</P>
<P>98. Zinner stated at Questioning and later at the within trial that legal research was necessary before he could provide any legal advice to Ashraf.
<P1>Transcript July 23, 2015, p 10, ll 10&ndash;12 [D.48]</P1></P>
<P>99. However, a competent solicitor should be able to advise the client regarding such basic procedural options as amending one's claim without conducting further research. Indeed, Mr. Newcombe states in his Expert Report that it should have been &ldquo;glaringly obvious&rdquo; that an amendment was the likely next step:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[...] it should, in my opinion, have been glaringly obvious to a reasonably competent barrister and solicitor that the quickest and most effective means of responding to SNC's application to strike the Statement of Claim would be to amend it to include a claim for constructive dismissal. To the extent that senior counsel like Mr. Zinner was not aware that applications to amend a claim are invariably dealt with before an application to strike a claim, even a modicum of inquiry into the matter should have revealed that to him. Further, as no defence had been filed, as noted by Mr. Justice Mahoney, it was open to Mr. Ashraf to amend his pleadings as of right. All of the foregoing would have been brought to Mr. Ashraf's attention by a reasonably competent barrister and solicitor, and the Defendants therefore failed to meet the standard of care expected of them</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Chad Newcomb Expert Opinion [Court Exhibit #10]</EM></P1></P>
<P>100. Zinner did not do any research before filing the claim when it was absolutely essential and instead relied on his 30 years of experience. But when it came to most procedural step such as amending the Statement of Claim he was no longer relying on his 30 years of litigation experience and took months to do research at the end of which time he advised discontinuing the action. This and so many other contradictory positions of Zinner on various issues is a mask hiding the truth.</P>
<P>101. Zinner admitted at Questioning that he had all but given up on Ashraf at that time because he was &ldquo;difficult, demanding and high-maintenance&rdquo;. However, not only giving up on a client in a manner he did is a breach of his duties but Zinner defamed Ashraf for what is his curiosity and interest is in his case when he was divided and almost demoralized when he heard one thing from Zinner and read something different in his works and when his action went down the drain because of the malevolent indifference of Zinner. This blames and accusation is false and childish and empty excuse to divert his own faults to his client. Moreover
<QUOTE><P><EM>[MR. ASHRAF]: [...] Did you advise Mr. Ashraf that he could amend his statement of claim or you could amend his statement of claim to that of contract as a defence against the application of the defendant</EM>?</P>
<P><EM>[MR. ZINNER]: Let me be perfectly open and clear. First and foremost, I felt that some proper legal research was required in order to properly address the next steps</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>Secondly, by this point in time, I was quite conflicted about whether or not I wanted to continue acting for Mr. Ashraf</EM>. <BOLD><EM>I found Mr. Ashraf to be a difficult, demanding and high-maintenance client</EM></BOLD>. <EM>He indicated to me that he no longer wanted to abide by the terms of our contract. He wanted to renegotiate the contract on the basis of terms which I wasn't all that enthusiastic about. I wasn't convinced that Mr. Ashraf had a totally winning case. And so</EM><BOLD><EM>for all of these reasons, I didn't take any more proactive steps on behalf of Mr. Ashraf</EM></BOLD>.</P></QUOTE>
Moreover, the Letter of Mr. Rooney dated April 23, 2018, to Steve Eichler, SNC Lawyer is in reference which is an evidence of misrepresenting the SNC action and the within action in every opportunity.
<P1>Transcript, July 23, 2015, p 116, ll 6&ndash;23 [D.48] [TAB 61]</P1></P>
<P>102. This failure to take &ldquo;any more proactive steps&rdquo; was in breach of the tortious and contractual duties owed to Ashraf. Zinner's duties to his client persisted, regardless of his state of mind regarding the Retainer Agreement. Indeed, Zinner admitted at Questioning that he was aware of his duty to provide legal advice to Ashraf for so long as he continued to be solicitor of record:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[MR. ASHRAF]: So, Mr. Zinner, your failure to get back to me and clearly say what your status is as far as a retainer and our relationship&mdash;the representation relationship is concerned, your failure to get back to me on those terms of revised payment scheme, would that excuse you from providing me proper legal advice, especially when you had told me you will continue to represent me until you make up your mind</EM>?</P>
<P><EM>[MR. ZINNER]: For so long as I continued to be the solicitor of record, I perceived that I had a duty to give you such advice as I could</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript, July 23, 2015, p 118, ll 6&ndash;16, [D.48]</P1></P>
<P>103. Therefore, the Defendants breached their tortious and contractual duties by failing to detect the potential WCA issue, failing to determine the correct limitation period for a constructive dismissal claim, failing to plead the only meritorious cause of action, and by failing to address those errors by properly advising Ashraf of his procedural options in a timely manner or at all.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>C &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>Summary Zinner's Breaches in Tort and Contract</EM></TI>
<P>104. It is submitted that Zinner's failure to plead the proper and/or all potential, causes of action and his understanding of the limitation issue as well as WCA application in the case was not only negligent, but it was a breach of contract too. The retainer agreement entered into by Ashraf and Zinner clearly contemplates time spent assessing the nature and merits of his possible claims against SNC Lavalin and legal research being conducted in support of this. Clearly, he did not consider the ramifications of bringing one action and not another, and no research into basic procedural steps or limitations law was conducted.</P>
<P>105. In summary, it is submitted that the followings amounted to acts of negligence and/or breach of contract by Zinner but not limited to:
<P1>a. Incorrect application of the plain wording of the <BOLD><EM>Limitations Act</EM></BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>b. Not being aware of when a claim for constructive dismissal arises;</P1>
<P1>c. framing the claim as a standalone tort when he knew, or should have known, that a tort claims for injuries against employers are barred by the <BOLD><EM>WCA Act</EM></BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>d. Failing in basic litigation procedural law as well as the law relevant to the matters he was then advising Ashraf on which required research that never happened before filing the claim;</P1>
<P1>e. Failing to review all the materials provided to him by Ashraf and, without limiting the generality of that, failing to read the medical records and reports provided by Ashraf, such that his legal opinion had to be revised not once, but twice to align his written opinion to what he had told Ashraf earlier in person-to-person discussions;</P1>
<P1>f. Noting the Defendants in default after they had served him with a summary judgment application within the negotiated limitation time,</P1>
<P1>g. Failing to advise Ashraf of meaningful strategy to move the action forward when faced with the summary judgment application for a lengthy period of several weeks during which he was considering whether or not to continue to act for Ashraf; and</P1>
<P1>h. Instead of amending the Statement of Claim when the pleadings were still open, he advised Ashraf to withdraw from the action,</P1>
<P1>i. Receiving payment in full satisfaction of his invoices without any objections and follow up and later reneging it when terminated,</P1>
<P1>j. In general, conduct tantamount to obstruction of justice by incorrect legal advice and incorrect framing of the cause of action in the statement of claim.</P1></P>
<P>106. A similar list is in [TAB 1] with most breaches in different categories showing relevant Plaintiff's Exhibit numbers.</P>
<P>107. It is further submitted that none of the above acts of negligence and breach of contract amount to &ldquo;mere errors in judgment.&rdquo; They do not represent simple mistakes, they indicate negligence if not deliberate harm, when he had the foreknowledge of the <EM>WCA</EM> constraints or at least lack of knowledge of the subject area that Zinner had told Ashraf he knew, a lack of willingness to do research or make enquiries into the merits of the proposed claim; a failure to review materials the client had provided him, then stating that the absence of such materials would be fatal to the claim (first and second drafts of his opinion letter) and, overall, an attitude of callousness if not sabotage of the Action. When alerted, Zinner did not correct his mistakes and instead was chasing Ashraf in several court hearings for payment in lieu of work which not only was of no value but fundamentally damaged Ashraf's claim paralyzing his life and well-being due to the added pain and suffering upon him. Before filing the Action, Zinner claimed the action was to progress unimpeded but when faced with opposition of the Defendant on the ground of WCA bar, he looked as if he never knew anything about it, as if his 30 years of experience upon which he relied not to do any research before filing the action had vanished and he refrained from giving obvious procedural legal advice and said he had to conduct research. He should have done the research before filing which he did not do and once he finished his research in October 2012, he asked Ashraf to discontinue the action if barred!</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>IV - III.</N><TI>The Defendants are liable for Plaintiff's suffering and damages resulting from Breaches of their Tortious and contractual duties</TI>
