<P>130. It is submitted, had Zinner started action 1201-09737, properly pled constructive dismissal and claimed for notice period and damages arising from the manner of dismissal such as defamations, loss of earning capacity to reengage in employment and thereby wage loss beyond notice period till at least age 65, due to stress; the action would have not suffered from damages that stained it to the end and Ashraf would have been allowed, as will be shown in the following authorities, to advance to trial all damages and not be limited to Aggravated and punitive damages which are the rubric for general none-pecuniary intangible emotional damages and limited with historical cap of $200 K in constructive dismissal cases.</P>
<P>131. The SCC has outlined in <CASEREF><SOC>Honda Canada Inc. v. Keays</SOC></CASEREF>, which was adjudicated several years before Zinner filed a statement of Claim for Ashraf, the principles for constructive dismissal and damages flowing from it which as of this date is still the leading authority in causes of action for constructive dismissal.</P>
<P>132. The law relating to damages for <BOLD>mental distress and intentional infliction of mental suffering</BOLD> arising from wrongful or constructive dismissal context is seen in the line of decisions stemming from <CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v. United Grain Growers</SOC><CITE>[1997] 3 S.C.R. 701</CITE></CASEREF>, as explained by <CASEREF><SOC>Honda Canada Inc. v. Keays</SOC></CASEREF>, in paragraphs 55 to 59, which are reviewed herein. ...
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Honda Canada Inc. v. Keays</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 39</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(CanLII)</EM>, in paragraphs 55 to 59 [TAB 20]</P1></P>
<P>133. It is submitted that the above reviewed excerpts establish the following principles: Wholly apart from damages in lieu of notice, other losses arising from the manner in which the employee was dismissed (not from the dismissal itself) are compensable if, at the time the employment contract was entered into, such losses were contemplated: Wallace, Honda, et seq., &ldquo;<EM>Damages attributable to conduct in the manner of dismissal are always to be awarded under the</EM><BOLD><EM>Hadley principle</EM></BOLD><EM>&rdquo; Honda, at para. [59]. That principle is that damages are recoverable for a contractual breach if the damages are &ldquo;such as may fairly and reasonably be considered either arising naturally ... from such breach of contract itself or such as may reasonably be supposed to have been in the contemplation of parties.&rdquo;, Honda, at para [55]</EM></P>
<P>134. At least since <BOLD><EM>Wallace</EM></BOLD><EM>(1997)</EM> and <BOLD><EM>Fidler</EM></BOLD><EM>(1854)</EM>, the law has recognized that both parties to an employment contract have an expectation that an employer will be civil, reasonable, honest and forthright, and otherwise act in good faith, in the course of a dismissal of the employee. Failure to act in accordance with this expectation lead accordingly to foreseeable and compensable damages, and therefore damages arising from such failure fall under the <BOLD><EM>Hadley</EM></BOLD> principle. Such damages should be awarded in a manner that reflects the &ldquo;<BOLD><EM>ACTUAL</EM></BOLD>&rdquo; damage sustained: <EM>Honda</EM>, para. 59.</P>
<P>135. There is nothing, in law or in the evidence, to suggest that Ashraf's constructive dismissal claim is limited to a claim for damages in lieu of notice, or that he is otherwise unable to seek damages, arising from the manner of his dismissal whether pecuniary or none-pecuniary, for mental distress or any other similar consequential losses recognized as a head of damage in constructive dismissal.</P>
<P>136. It is without saying that majority of resignations or terminations are stressful as job changes even when not in bad faith and for better are not without stress how much more if unemployment or injuries due to bad faith is accompanied in a termination or resignation. But damages due to stress in claims arising from the manner by which an employee is constructively dismissed are especially compensable when proven that the manner was in violation of duty of good faith and duty of care by employer and through intentional infliction of mental suffering to force the employee out of employment while damaging his health, reputations, or damaging his economic interests and etc.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v. United Grain Growers Ltd</SOC><CITE>[1997] 3 SCR 701</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>1997 CanLII 332</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>at para. 95</EM>., [TAB 55]</P1></P>
<P>137. The following authorities clearly demonstrate by differentiation what is meant by a claim for damages due to stress in wrongful or constructive dismissal case.</P>
<P>138. The case of <CASEREF><SOC>Piresferreira v. Ayotte</SOC><CITE>2008 canlii67418</CITE></CASEREF>, is a good precedence for the case of Ashraf versus SNC for damages arising from the manner of his dismissal. The employee alleged constructive dismissal and damages due to stress arising from the manner thereof. The court awarded her among other damages payment with respect to proper notice as well as wage loss till age 65, due to loss of capacity to reengage in work which resulted from the stress in the manner of her constructive dismissal.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Piresferreira v. Ayotte</SOC><CITE>2008 canlii67418</CITE></CASEREF>, [TAB 45]</P1></P>
<P>139. On appeal, the wage loss award was dismissed not on the ground that the law does not allow it but on the ground that her evidence was insufficient to support her claim for Intentional Infliction of Mental Suffering (IIMS). The Appeal court stated that there was well established and recorded investigation at Bell Mobility, the supervisor at fault who was the cause of stress was subjected to disciplinary action, the supervisor had to write a formal letter of apology to the wronged employee with copy to HR in addition to an in-person apology at a meeting with the HR. The employer assigned the employee, Piresferreira to a different supervisor. The employer transferred the abusive supervisor to a different location in the company to avoid encounters. The Appeal court in their decision stated based on all these facts the employer had done everything possible to accommodate the employee which showed lack of intent on the part of the corporation to give rise to intentional infliction of mental suffering.</P>
<P>140. In Ashraf's case there was no investigation at the time and no records was even produced during its litigation, absolutely nothing in his HR file not even a copy of three months disciplinary action and warning in the form of PIP, (The Performance Improvement Plan, which is in Ashraf's Book of Exhibit, Exhibit #D.8) and the accusation therein were not supported by any facts and evidence at the time and nothing was produce from his HR file and nothing in the cross examinations of SNC officers but purely acts of intimidation, bullying, marginalization, humiliation and etc.</P>
<P>141. There are several evidences of Ashraf's communications before his complete disability to the management team that how the stress born of abusive systematic campaign (planned, intentional) is causing him sickness. One is an email which is in Plaintiff Book of Exhibit #D.66 from Ashraf to his director of Engineering G. Brook a couple of months before his total disability. Not only the management did not take any steps to investigate the issues, they worsened their systematic intentional approach of forcing him out with another 2009-year end negative performance review given to him on Jan 6, 2010, till eventually he collapsed in complete sickness due to ungrounded and unjustified false accusations one after another. A year later, when Ashraf wrote to the employer expressing his willingness to take part in gradual return to work plan, initiated by Sun Life, the employer did not even respond.</P>
<P>142. The pile of evidence specially what has been gathered is overwhelming beyond a shadow of doubt, to support all the allegations Ashraf had brought to court, and there has to be an opportunity in the trial within trial to unburden justice from its obstruction.</P>
<P>143. Another popular case to cite with respect to claims for loss of income beyond notice period which had arisen from constructive dismissal, <CASEREF><SOC>Boucher v. Wal-Mart Canada Corp.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 419</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(CanLII)</EM>, in which the same law is shown in its paragraphs [102&ndash;105]. ...
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Boucher v. Wal-Mart Canada Corp.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 419</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(CanLII)</EM>, [TAB 46]</P1></P>
<P>144. In <CASEREF><SOC>Silvera v. Olympia Jewellery</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3760</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(CanLII)</EM>, the young employee who was found constructively dismissed was awarded wage loss in addition and beyond pay for proper notice period until her full recovery which lasted for about three years till she was able to reengage in work.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Silvera v. Olympia Jewellery</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 3760</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(CanLII)</EM>, [TAB 47]</P1></P>
<P>145. In <CASEREF><SOC>Potter v. New Brunsswick LAS</SOC><CITE>2015scc10</CITE><PAGENUM>pages 501, 501</PAGENUM><PARANUM>[21] and [27]</PARANUM></CASEREF> of [TAB 21], which is another case of precedence derived from <CASEREF><SOC>Honda v. Keays</SOC></CASEREF>, the SCC upheld the decisions of the lower courts which went back several years before 2012, and clearly stated that determination of constructive dismissal in common law need not formal resignation or termination....
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Potter v. New Brunsswick LAS</SOC><CITE>2015scc10</CITE></CASEREF>, [TAB 21]</P1></P>
<P>146. However, in the case at bar, Ashraf had informed SNC and Sun Life after repeated attempts seeking resolution which remained without response that he was not going to return to his employment at SNC. The evidences of these facts are in memos and emails Ashraf sent to the senior management of SNC which are Plaintiff's Exhibit D.8. Also, a letter of Ashraf's physician, Dr. Thomas to Sun Life dated August 30, 2011, which is in Plaintiff's Exhibit D.8.10 med/SL, informing Sun Life and SNC that Ashraf is not returning to work for SNC.</P>
<P>147. The SCC had also articulated the law in terms of what constitutes wrongful constructive dismissal in the same case of <CASEREF><SOC>Potter v. New Brunsswick</SOC></CASEREF> LAS <BOLD>2015</BOLD>scc10: Page 502, Para 2:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Constructive dismissal can take two forms: that of a single unilateral act that breaches an essential term of the contract, or that of a series of acts that, taken together, show that the employer intended to no longer be bound by the contract</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>148. In the SNC action it is clear that any excuses by Zinner for not having alleged constructive dismissal for lack of formal termination/resignation or a single event one which by itself is considered a unilateral act in breach of the employment contract is indefensible: as series of intentional and unilateral acts of SNC in their abusive systematic campaign from 2007 to 2010, when taken together, show that SNC intended to no longer be bound by the employment contract. Not withstanding that many single acts of SNC on its own constitute a breach of contract and ground for constructive dismissal.</P>
<P>149. Ashraf however had a duty as an employee to mitigate his losses and continued working while protesting violations of terms of his contract and the abusive conduct of SNC hoping for improvements. However the more resilience Ashraf demonstrated in bringing to attention of the management the operational mismanagement and abusive behavior of his supervisor and his team and to clear any possible misunderstanding, the worst and more vehement became the abusive campaign orchestrated and/or condoned by the senior management to force him out of employment or construct and craft enough evidence which in reality were false but to the onlookers may have seemed as justified to have Ashraf terminated. SNC succeeded as they knew full well Ashraf had become very sick with diagnosis of auto immune disease and lupus in September 2009, the cause of which was communicated to the management to have been stress arising from the abusive conducts of his supervisor and the senior management of the corporation. SNC Exhibit entered as 1401 Exhibit D.66, is in reference which is one of the evidences in an email dated Nov 2009.</P>
<P>150. As also shown in <CASEREF><SOC>Prinzo v. Baycrest Centre for Geriatric Care</SOC><CITE>2002 CanLII 45005</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, actionable wrongs resulting in injuries must arise from clearly pled cause of Action for constructive dismissal. On its own as a standalone tort similar to Zinner's framing, without directly alleging constructive dismissal would fall under jurisdiction of <EM>WCA</EM> and barred accordingly.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Prinzo v. Baycrest Centre for Geriatric Care</SOC><CITE>2002 CanLII 45005</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [TAB 48]</P1></P>
<P>151. It is submitted the work performed by Zinner on behalf of Ashraf was performed with conscious gross negligence, in breach of contract, in breach of fiduciary duty, in breach of duty of care, in breach of code of ethics of the law society, in breach of client's trust. And as a result, not only Ashraf suffered financial losses, but his health worsened losing any chance of recovery and remission during the earlier period of his disease when he was placed on disability to find an opportunity for recuperation and recovery.</P>
<P>152. Incorrect legal advice is causative of damage if it is the &ldquo;direct, immediate and logical cause&rdquo; in pursuing a particular course of conduct. Causation is not severed by receiving a second legal opinion, even if that opinion is incorrect:
<QUOTE><P><EM>In the circumstances as revealed by the evidence, one must necessarily conclude that the appellant notary's opinion was the direct, immediate, and logical cause of the respondents' decision not to purchase the property. Had the appellant given proper legal advice, as the respondents testified, they would never have needed to seek a second opinion</EM>. <BOLD><EM>The fact that the second legal opinion was also erroneous in law could only have been, on the facts of this case, a ground for legal proceedings against that notary, provided causation could have been established. It cannot affect the causal link between the appellant's fault and the damage suffered by the respondents</EM>.</BOLD><EM>The very fact that the appellant alone was sued, and not the second notary, demonstrates that in the respondents' estimation, it was the appellant's opinion that motivated their refusal to purchase the property</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dorion v Roberge</SOC><CITE>[1991] 1 SCR 374</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1991] SCJ No 15</CITE><PARANUM>210</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 32]</P1></P>
<P>153. The above passage directly contradicts the Defendants' contention that the subsequent legal advice obtained by Ashraf breaks the chain of causation, or that Ashraf was somehow the author of his own misfortune.</P>
<P>154. Despite his reluctance, Ashraf was hands-on during the drafting of Zinner's opinion or the Statement Claim to the degree of synchronizing Zinner's earlier legal advice he gave Ashraf in person to what he wrote in his letters or the events and transactions which he had told Ashraf he was to plead in the claim but were not shown in his drafts. Ashraf had no part whatsoever in formulating the law, cause of action or legal pleadings. However, it is submitted that a lawyer has a duty of competence that applies equally to every client, whether &ldquo;high-maintenance&rdquo; or not. Further, Ashraf's approval of the Statement of Claim was premised upon the Defendants' faulty legal opinion, including his incorrect assumption about the limitation date applicable to a constructive dismissal claim and his failure to advise Ashraf of the existence of the <EM>WCA</EM> bar.
<P1>Transcript of Questioning of Shidan Ashraf, July 21, 2015, p 16, ll 4&ndash;11 [D.48]</P1></P>
<P>155. As argued in the above parts, Zinner breached the requisite standard of care and the Retainer Agreement by failing to plead constructive dismissal in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>156. The Defendants contend that Ashraf obtained legal advice that advised him that he could amend his claim, and the Defendants are not responsible for Ashraf's failure to follow that advice. This position is legally indefensible in light of the Supreme Court of Canada's holding in <CASEREF><SOC>Dorion v Roberge</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM>, cited above at paragraph 151. Further, despite this advice, Ashraf remained unaware that he could amend without leave, or while the application to strike was pending. Even Master Laycock appeared to be under the misapprehension that pleadings were closed:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[MR. ASHRAF]: [...] I asked [Master Laycock] to allow me to amend my statement of claim to constructive dismissal. He told me to bring an application and take permission because he has&mdash;is dismissing the case. And so I brought an application which was heard by subsequent hearing</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Transcript of Questioning of Shidan Ashraf, July 21, 2015, p 40, ll 10&ndash;15 [D.48]</P1></P>
<P>157. Consequently, at a minimum, the steps taken arose out of Zinner's inadequate legal analysis and incorrect legal advice.</P>
<P>158. However, even after the constructive dismissal claim was added, Justice Mahoney held that the statutory bar under the <EM>WCA</EM> also removed that cause of action:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Mr. Ashraf's claim for damages for constructive dismissal in his draft Amended Statement of Claim arises out of the same allegations of systemic abuse, harassment and bullying, and the amendments relate to the same series of events. Adding a claim for constructive dismissal in these circumstances does not alter my conclusion that Mr. Ashraf's allegations fall under the definition of &ldquo;accident&rdquo; for the purpose of workers' compensation</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf vSNC Lavalin ATP Inc</SOC><CITE>2013 ABQB 688</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Tab 29]</P1></P>
<P>159. The Court of Appeal, in reversing Justice Mahoney's decision, noted that this error arose out of the learned Justice's interpretation of the WCA Act which is not applicable to physical or psychological injuries due to stress arising from the SNC Action in the manner of Ashraf's dismissal.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ashraf v SNC Lavalin ATP Inc</SOC><CITE>2015 ABCA 78</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 18]</P1></P>
<P>160. Zinner's negligent characterization of the SNC Action poisoned the well to such an extent that it overshadowed the &ldquo;essential character&rdquo; of the SNC Action, even after constructive dismissal was expressly pled. A second look by the Court of Appeal was required which provided further clarifications on the claims of constructive dismissal but due to the <BOLD>stigma</BOLD> attached to the SNC action caused by Zinner's negligence, it was deterred from providing the remedies provisioned by the SCC to constructive dismissal actions which started properly in their true cause of action with damages pled accordingly.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>ii</EM></N><TI><EM>Liability of Zinner for the restorative litigation work</EM></TI>
<P>161. Damages for a lawyer's negligence include the legal costs of rectifying his mistakes.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Beazer v Tollestrup Estate</SOC><CITE>2017 ABCA 429</CITE><PARANUM>94</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 49]</P1></P>
<P>162. In particular, legal costs are recoverable when they were incurred by the Plaintiff while taking the proper legal steps to mitigate his damages, even when the steps taken were ultimately fruitless:
<QUOTE><P><EM>In my view these were costs properly incurred by the plaintiff in endeavouring to preserve his action and its failure to do so would have permitted the defendants herein to claim he did not take appropriate steps to mitigate his damages. They might, if he had not chosen to defend the motion or to take all available appeals from the Master's order, have argued that the action would have survived if he had taken all available steps to protect it. I allow those damages, notwithstanding the fact that I have found the plaintiff would not have succeeded in the libel action</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Gouzenko v Harris</SOC><YEAR>1976</YEAR><CITE>13 OR (2d) 730</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>72 DLR (3d) 293</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont HCJ</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 84 [TAB 50]</P1></P>
<P>163. Consequently, it is submitted that Zinner is liable for all the litigation work and resulting losses. The work done was absolutely essential to restore the dead action and repair and revive its claim to the extent possible. These damages resulted directly from Zinner's professional negligence and breach of his contract and the extent of all the work would have been unnecessary if Zinner started the action properly in the correct cause of Action.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>B &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>Zinner is labile for the Plaintiff's mental distress and worsening of his illnesses suffered while salvaging the SNC Action</EM></TI>
<P>164. Zinner is liable for foreseeable injuries caused by his negligence, including mental injuries.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Saadati v Moorhead</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 28</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 22]</P1></P>
<P>165. Similarly, contractual damages include damages for mental distress where &ldquo;the prospect of mental distress upon breach [was] within the reasonable contemplation of the parties at the time the contract was made.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Fidler v Sun Life Assurance Co of Canada</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 30</CITE><PARANUM>56</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 23]</P1></P>
<P>166. The fact that the Plaintiff was ill prior to retaining Zinner does not relieve Zinner of liability. The law does not excuse a defendant from liability merely because other causal factors for which he is not responsible also helped produce the harm. This principle applies to any case in which the injuries caused by a number of factors are indivisible.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>G(ED) v Hammer</SOC><CITE>2003 SCC 52</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 24]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Athey v Leonati</SOC><CITE>[1996] 3 SCR 458</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1996] SCJ No 102</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 25]</P1></P>
<P>167. The doctrine of mitigation of damages has no place in a personal injury claim.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Andrews v Grand &amp; Toy Alberta Ltd</SOC><CITE>[1978] 2 SCR 229</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1978] SCJ No 6</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <EM>[Andrews]</EM> at para 21 [TAB 26]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Silvaniuk v Stevens</SOC><CITE>1999 ABCA 191</CITE><PARANUM>31-32</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 27]</P1></P>
<P>168. The Defendants had committed as part of condition of their retainer to provide legal service which were to be as seamless as possible to the Plaintiff due to conditions of his health. The Defendants were clearly aware of Ashraf's susceptibility to stress and anxiety, and the impact that stress has on his physical and mental wellbeing. It was reasonably foreseeable that imposing undue stress on Ashraf would occasion physical and mental injury.</P>
<P>169. Causation of Ashraf disabilities is established in various medical expert opinion reports and letters entered as evidence in the Trial Court Exhibit #7. It is caused by undue stress in the manner of dismissal of Ashraf and Zinner's professional negligence in prolonged years of pain and suffering while salvaging the SNC Action which has directly contributed to exacerbation and worsening of Ashraf's physical and psychological health.</P>
<P>170. The opinion of psychiatrist Dr. Asha Nair supports the conclusion that the Defendants' breaches directly caused Ashraf's ongoing issues with anxiety:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Overall, Mr. Ashraf seems to have struggled both from physical and mental health perspective [sic] due to ongoing stressors and pressures of going through a litigation process. [...]</EM></P>
<P><EM>Overall, my impression of Mr. Ashraf's mental health remains the same in that he has continued to experience symptoms of anxiety that initially was triggered and maintained by work related stressors and, over the last few years, due to the stressors of dealing with the legal system, especially as a self-represented litigant</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Report of Dr. Asha Nair dated April 12, 2018 [Court Exhibit #7]</P1></P>
<P>171. The opinion of rheumatologist Dr. Dianne Mosher confirmed that Ashraf's increased stress while undertaking the SNC Action aggravated his psoriatic arthritis:
<QUOTE><P><EM>At the request of Mr. Ashraf, I have agreed to provide further information on his condition of psoriatic arthritis and the relationship of his disease to the ongoing stress of litigation.... Mr. Ashraf was referred to me by Dr. Jibb upon her retirement. I originally saw Mr. Ashraf on June 29, 2015. ... He has required aggressive therapy this has only partially controlled his disease.... In my expert opinion, I believe that the undue stress Mr. Ashraf has been under has contributed to the severity and progression of his psoriatic arthritis. In addition, this has affected his emotional wellbeing</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Report of Dr. Dianne Mosher dated Feb 6, 2019 [Court Exhibit #7]</P1></P>
<P>172. She also shown through the laboratory test results in her letter of October 15, 2018, as well as the above-mentioned letter that the undue stress caused by the litigation over the years has made many different medications she has tried on Ashraf, ineffective. These are medications used to control and bring about remission, but Ashraf still has significant internal inflammation including in his joints, skin and nervous system which are attributed to continued stress of the litigation. Not only Ashraf could not benefit from the medication due to ongoing stress of the litigation, but he has to suffer from the adverse side effects of the same in addition to the symptoms of his disease. The most manifest and simplest of the side effects is weakening of the immune system by design which make Ashraf extremely susceptible to infections.</P>
<P>173. In his Medical Expert Opinion Reports and subsequent letters expressing the same, <BOLD>Dr. Thomas</BOLD> who was a practicing physician in family medicine and also a professor at the medical school of UOC involved in highly advanced research, stated clearly that <UNDER>undue stress</UNDER> at work and <UNDER>prolonged litigation as self-represented litigant</UNDER>, had been primary contributing factor in causation, worsening and exacerbation of Ashraf's physical and psychological disease, including depression, post traumatic syndromes and anxiety disorder which based on scientific analysis he presented at the trial as a witness, not only have crippling effect on one's life causing much pain and suffering but shorten the life of patients by years.</P>
<P>174. There is also a consult note for a visit in 2009, in Exhibits # D.8, with Ashraf's dermatologist specialist physician, Dr. Storwick, in which note he diagnosed Ashraf's Lupus and stated it was caused by stress which had played a role in his disease.</P>
<P>175. It goes without saying if a person is suffering from smoke inhalation, not only the patient is treated for the same but the fire causing the smoke has to be put out otherwise no remedy can heal the symptoms while the causation actively continues.</P>
<P>176. It was reasonably foreseeable that Ashraf would suffer mental distress and an aggravation of his physical symptoms when forced to make nearly two dozen court applications as a direct result of his lawyer's negligence.</P>
<P>177. As a result of the Defendants' breaches, Ashraf was left financially incapable of retaining a lawyer to take care of the SNC Action on his behalf, and instead had to represent himself while obtaining piecemeal legal assistance.
<P1>Transcript of Questioning of Shidan Ashraf, July 21, 2015, p 35 l 14 - p 36, l 17 [D.46]</P1></P>
<P>178. By the time Ashraf terminated the Retainer Agreement, he had already paid thousands of dollars in legal fees to the Defendants. Ashraf was, and continues to be, relying on long term disability benefits for income. Spending thousands of dollars by gambling on another lawyer simply was not an option.
<P1>Transcript of Continued Questioning of Shidan Ashraf, December 16, 2015, p 81, l 17 - p 82, l 2 [D.46]</P1></P>
<P>179. Ashraf was placed in a difficult situation after Zinner refused to reimburse him with the retainer money in the amount of $5,000.00 kept as a float. The difficulty and mental distress were because SNC action on which Ashraf's future livelihood and retirement income and care depended had sunk very fast, he was already out of pocket for close to $9,000.00 ($8,750.00) for direct payments to Zinner. He was neither in a position to hire another lawyer by way of a lump sum retainer deposit as many lawyers who looked at the history of the case felt somewhat electrocuted and did not want to dig into such a mess or alternatively wanted many folds more than a normal case, nor was Ashraf able to engage in some kind of part time work to be able to afford the restorative litigation cost ahead of him which at the time did not seem to be involving 7 years of litigation.</P>
<P>180. The mental anguish and distress caused by the shock of the above circumstances resulting in worsening of his psychological and physical health on one hand and unknown in the litigation like a blind man without his cane in the grand canyons on the other were major cause of his worsening health.</P>
<P>181. The Defendants' breaches left Ashraf in such a financial and emotional state that he was practically forced to self-represent himself in a multimillion-dollar lawsuit. Given Ashraf's susceptibility to stress-related illness, a susceptibility which was known to the Defendants, they are liable for Ashraf's mental and physical deterioration arising out of the extensive litigation he was forced to undertake.</P>
<P>182. As the result, Ashraf has lost his rightful entitlement of providing basic life and care for himself after age 65 when survival will be unlikely to achieve as his resources are depleted and the provision of reasonable pension is lost to him due to professional negligence of Zinner unless he is vindicated in this trial and in the SNC trial within the trial of this action.</P>
<P>183. In summary Zinner is liable for all pain and suffering and all direct and indirect damages Zinner's professional negligence and breach of contract has brought upon Ashraf.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>C &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>The Defendants' breaches caused the Plaintiff to settle the SNC Action prematurely</EM></TI>
<P>184. The burden of proof is on the Plaintiff to establish, on a balance of probabilities, that &ldquo;but for&rdquo; Zinner's substandard conduct (whether characterized as negligent or in breach of contract), Ashraf would have continued pursuing the SNC Action, rather than settling prematurely.
<P1><EM>Handerek</EM>, <EM>supra at para 201 [TAB 6]</EM></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clements (Litigation Guardian of) v Clements</SOC><CITE>2012 SCC 32</CITE><PARANUM>8 and 46</PARANUM></CASEREF> <EM>[TAB 30]</EM></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Houweling Nurseries Ltd v Fisons Western Corp</SOC><CITE>[1988] BCJ No 306</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>49 DLR (4h) 205</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [TAB 31], at Para 19, <EM>cited with approval in Handerek</EM>, <EM>supra at para 201 and</EM> <CASEREF><SOC>Extreme Excavating &amp; Backhoe Services Ltd v Scott</SOC><CITE>2018 ABQB 102</CITE><PARANUM>86</PARANUM></CASEREF>., [TAB 56]</P1></P>
<P>185. Incorrect legal advice is causative of damage if it is the &ldquo;direct, immediate and logical cause&rdquo; in pursuing a particular course of conduct. Causation is not severed by receiving a second legal opinion, even if that opinion is incorrect.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Dorion v Roberge</SOC><CITE>[1991] 1 SCR 374</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1991] SCJ No 15</CITE><PARANUM>210</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 32]</P1></P>
<P>186. The <BOLD>stigma</BOLD> of the initial problems which tainted the Action to its end, particularly those with respect to the framing of the claims for damages with respect to loss of earning capacity arising from his manner of dismissal (as opposed to those arising from his employment, which are not and never were in issue) created a situation in which Ashraf was only allowed by the Appeal Court to advance only small part of his claim to trial.</P>
<P>187. Moreover, the incorrect advice of Zinner about the limitation time prevented Ashraf from proceeding to trial in the SNC action. He was faced with much higher risk of losing his case at the trial due to limitation issue which has a very high threshold than was actually appropriate and he lost opportunity of recovering whatever damages were allowed and escalating his claims for other damages to the Appeal Court and Supreme Court of Canada in the context of correct law of constructive dismissal if not successful at the trial.</P>
<P>188. Consequently, Ashraf also suffered a series of anxiety attacks in November 2017, just prior to scheduled trial in the SNC Action and this was another reason Ashraf was forced to settle the SNC Action. The action was resolved for significantly less than it was worth in order to salvage what he could of his claim. Ashraf's family physician, Dr. Roger Thomas, confirmed that Ashraf's anxiety attacks in November 2017 forced him to settle the SNC Action prematurely.
<P1>Letter from Dr. Roger Thomas dated January 26, 2018 and enclosed chart dated November 20, 2017 [Court Exhibit #7]</P1></P>
<P>189. It is enough to fix liability if one could foresee the loss or injury in a general way. The extent of the damage and its manner of incidence need not be foreseeable if the type of loss or injury was foreseeable.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Assiniboine South School Division No 3 v Greater Winnipeg Gas Co</SOC><CITE>[1971] 4 WWR 746</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1971] MJ No 39</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>MBCA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[1973] SCR vi (note)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1973] SCJ No 48</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> [TAB 38]</P1></P>
<P>190. As argued <EM>supra</EM> at paragraph 164, the Defendants are liable for the harm inflicted upon Ashraf's physical and mental wellbeing. It is submitted that the Defendants are also, therefore, liable for the reasonably foreseeable consequences of Ashraf's mental and physical injuries, including Ashraf's loss of capacity to fully litigate the SNC Action.</P>
<P>191. Ashraf circumstances would have been different Healthwise and otherwise in negotiating a settlement or in the trial of November 2017 and he would have not had to settle for the amount he did had it not been for Zinner's incorrect legal advice about the &ldquo;limitation problems&rdquo; with the claims, as discussed in the preceding paragraphs.</P>
<P>192. The Parties have agreed to address the proper judicially-assessed value of the SNC Action at a later stage in these proceedings. However, Ashraf's position is that the judicially-assessed value of the SNC Action will significantly exceed the value of the settlement obtained.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>D &gt;</EM></N><TI><EM>Zinner's Liabilities arising out of the premature settlement of the SNC Action</EM></TI>
<P>193. In professional negligence cases such as this, measure of both liability and damages are assessed as being the amount the plaintiff would have recovered in the SNC action 1201-09737 &ldquo;but for&rdquo; the negligence of the lawyer, the Defendant in this case. Thus a &ldquo;trial within a trial&rdquo; must be held, in order to establish liability and damages in that action, as well.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Luft v Zinkhofer</SOC><CITE>2016 ABQB 182</CITE><PARANUM>353 and 354</PARANUM></CASEREF> <EM>et seq., [TAB 33]</EM></P1></P>
<P>194. Damages for Zinner's breach of his tortious and contractual duties is measured by the amount that the Plaintiff would have been awarded, had the action not been derailed in the first place to lose major parts of its claim and had Ashraf not been forced to settle prematurely in light of Zinner's flawed legal advice. The value of what the Plaintiff lost is assessed by performing a &ldquo;trial within a trial.&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Handerek</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 220 [TAB 6]</P1></P>
<P>195. This Court recently explained the continuum of outcomes of the &ldquo;trial within a trial&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Handerek</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at paras 229&ndash;231 [TAB 6]</P1></P>
<P>196. Accordingly, it is submitted that the difference between the amount Ashraf actually recovered from SNC Lavalin and the amount he could have recovered, absent Zinner's negligence and breaches of contract, is an injury sustained as a direct result of Zinner's negligence and breach of contract for which Zinner is liable.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>IV - IV.</N><TI>The Defendants breached the fiduciary duty owed to the Plaintiff</TI>
<P>197. The relationship between a lawyer and client is fiduciary in nature, as well. The fiduciary duty may be broader than any contractual duties.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Strother v. 3464920 Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2007] 2 SCR 177</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2007 SCC 24</CITE><PARANUM>1</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, <EM>[TAB 34]</EM></P1></P>
<P>198. A lawyer owes a fiduciary duty to his client. A fiduciary breach may only be founded on breaches of the specific obligations imposed because of the fiduciary character of the relationship.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Perez v Galambos</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 48</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 11]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>International Corona Resources Ltd v LAC Minerals Ltd</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 SCR 574</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1989] SCJ No 83</CITE><PARANUM>28</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 35].</P1></P>
<P>199. Concurrent liability exists between fiduciary duty and contract, as well.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Luscar Ltd. v. Pembina Resources Limited</SOC><CITE>1994 ABCA 356</CITE><PARANUM>46</PARANUM></CASEREF>, [TAB 36]</P1></P>
<P>200. As part of his fiduciary duty, Zinner owed a duty of loyalty to the Plaintiff. The Alberta Court of Appeal has explained the duty of loyalty as follows. ...
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ramrakha v Zinner</SOC><CITE>[1994] AJ No 816</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>24 Alta LR (3d) 240</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>ABCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>[Zinner]</EM> at para 103, [TAB 37]</P1></P>
<P>201. For example, a solicitor acting for parties on both sides of a transaction creates a conflict of interest and constitutes a breach of fiduciary duty.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ramrakha v. Zinner</SOC><CITE>1994 CarswellAlta 247</CITE><PARANUM>65</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 37]</P1></P>
<P>202. However, the duty of loyalty is not limited to avoiding conflicts of interest. There are three dimensions to the duty of loyalty....
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v Neil</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 70</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 41]</P1></P>
<P>203. The Supreme Court of Canada recently emphasized the paramount importance of the duty of resolute advocacy. ...
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Groia v Law Society of Upper Canada</SOC><CITE>2018 SCC 27</CITE><PARANUM>72-73</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 42]</P1></P>
<P>204. Bad, incorrect and wrong legal advice constitute a breach of fiduciary duty even an &ldquo;innocent and honest bit of bad advice&rdquo; that may constitute a breach of fiduciary duty.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hodgkinson v Simms</SOC><CITE>[1994] 3 SCR 377</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1994] SCJ No 84</CITE><PARANUM>80</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [TAB 43]</P1></P>
<P>205. That is to say, when a lawyer strongly dissuades his client against pursuing a claim based upon an incomplete assessment of the merits of the case, he abdicates his role both as a competent advocate and as a resolute advocate.</P>
<P>206. Invoicing a client with incorrect descriptions and hours by a lawyer also constitutes a breach of the fiduciary duty owed to the client. In doing so, the lawyer puts his own monetary interest ahead of his client's, entitling the client to equitable relief.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Phillips Legal Profession Corp v Holm</SOC><CITE>2013 SKPC 2</CITE><PARANUM>66&ndash;79</PARANUM></CASEREF> [TAB 44]</P1></P>
<P>207. The purpose of the Retainer Agreement was to advise &ldquo;whether [Ashraf had] a valid and meritorious cause of action against SNC Lavalin.&rdquo; When Zinner formed his doubts about Ashraf case, he should have disclosed them to Ashraf. By keeping these doubts about matters relevant to the retainer to himself while continuing on as solicitor of record, Zinner breached his duty of candor and thereby breached duty he owed as a fiduciary to Ashraf.</P>
<P>208. It is submitted that once the solicitor learns that he has made a significant error in the work performed for a client, he should, out of this duty take all reasonable steps to ameliorate that error whether retained at the time or not. Zinner did nothing to ameliorate the effects of his negligence, but, instead, demonstrated a malevolent attitude of disinterest, engaged in other damaging activities and incorrect legal advice and pressured Ashraf after he was terminated for payments of statement of account for wasteful services rendered which not only were of no value but severely damaged the claim and the Action.</P>
<P>209. It was obvious that Zinner was under external influence of 3<SUP>rd</SUP> parties in breach of his fiduciary duty and contract right from the time he was drafting his opinion letter. He had advised Ashraf in one way when meeting with him but when he summarized his advice in writing in his July 12, 2012 letter, it was completely a different thing. When Ashraf met with him and reminded him of what he had told him a few days earlier, Zinner redrafted the letter and date it to July 16, 2012. Although the legal advice was closer to what he had told Ashraf earlier, it still had issues contrary to the facts and evidence shown him. At no time Ashraf imposed his view on any of the issues other than acting as feedback to align Zinner's written opinion to the earlier spoken advise and understandings. Zinner never said he had changed his mind. It was obvious he was writing his opinions to please other parties who were not present in his meetings with Ashraf to know what he had told him. But then when he noticed Ashraf was going to go ahead and start the action based on his person to person assurance that the claim will advance unimpeded, he betrayed the trust of his client and planted two bars in the claim by consciously and intentionally not pleading breach of contract according to his admission in the questioning of July 23, 2015, page 113, lines 16-17, which he confirmed in his cross examination at the trial: <EM>&ldquo;As I said, it wasn't intended to expressly mention contract or to aver that there was a contractual breach.&rdquo;</EM></P>
<P>210. Obviously, it is clear when breach of contract and constructive dismissal is not pled the injuries are interpreted to have arisen from employment and not from the manner of dismissal and thereby the court had no choice but to treat it as such with the WCA bar.</P>
<P>211. At one point, Zinner stated during the same questioning session that he was aware of the WCA bar to the tort action he commenced on behalf of Ashraf. If this was the case, commencing an action he knew was barred was a direct breach of trust. If it was not the case, then it was negligent of him not to have researched or not to have known this basic principle of Alberta law, as discussed in detail in the previous section.</P>
<P>212. The conflict of interest continued after filing the claim on July 31, 2012, through August to October and upon conducting the so called his research Zinner provided legal advice by way of a letter to the Defendant in SNC action that Ashraf should discontinue the action if his claim is dismissed by the master.</P>
<P>213. Zinner then compounded his breaches of duty in failing to take steps to ameliorate the errors he made in framing and drafting the claim (hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;wasted work&rdquo;) by not only billing Ashraf for the wasted work, but also by later reneging upon his termination on an agreement about reduction of charges in his invoices with respect to duplication of work or work not done which reneging resulted in not releasing the retainer amount to Ashraf which was kept as a float ($5,000.00), and taking him to multiple court hearings over more than a year.</P>
<P>214. It is submitted that in taking these series of steps, Zinner put his own interests ahead of Ashraf's, which amounts to a breach of his fiduciary duty.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Strother v. 3464920 Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2007] 2 SCR 177</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2007 SCC 24</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, [TAB 34]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Neil</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 70 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF>, [TAB 54]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clarke v. Perrick and FullJames</SOC><CITE>1996canlii1862</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF>, [TAB 5]</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Law Society of Alberta v Robert Burgener</SOC></CASEREF>, para 237, [TAB 17]</P1></P>
<P>215. It is respectfully submitted that the misconduct described above and listed below in bullet form, constitutes breach of the fiduciary duty owed by Zinner to Ashraf. In particular, Defendants breached their duties of zealous advocacy and candor by, in essence, giving up on Ashraf while remaining solicitor of record, and by failing to advise him of his procedural options concerning an imminent summary judgment application in a timely manner or at all. Further, Zinner admitted at Questioning (July 23, 2015, p 116, ll 20&ndash;23) that, at that point in time, he ceased &ldquo;taking proactive steps on behalf of Mr. Ashraf&rdquo; because he &ldquo;wasn't convinced that Mr. Ashraf had a totally winning case.&rdquo;
<P1>a. Issuing a statement of claim for personal injuries when he knew, or should have known, that it was barred by operation of the <EM>WCA Act</EM>;</P1>
<P1>b. Alternatively, failing to advise Ashraf that his standalone tort claim for injuries would have been barred by operation of the <EM>WCA</EM>;</P1>
<P1>c. Not pleading constructive dismissal which was not out of limitation time but pleadings standalone tort of injuries which was potentially out of time;</P1>
<P1>d. Failing to include a claim for defamation, breach of contract and constructive dismissal and the tortious conduct arising from the manner of dismissal in the Statement of Claim;</P1>
<P1>e. After months of so-called research, Zinner advised Ashraf through a letter addressed to the opposing counsel that Ashraf would <UNDER>discontinue</UNDER> his claim if it was barred by the <EM>WCA</EM>,</P1>
<P1>f. Keeping Ashraf in suspense for two months after Ashraf wanted to terminate him in August 15, 2012 meeting, under the false pretense that he would accept a semi-contingency payment scheme but just needed a few days to think;</P1>
<P1>g. Failing to provide legal advice or meaningful services to Ashraf while deciding for two months whether or not he wanted to continue to act for him which is tantamount to ceasing to act and/or abandoning a client;</P1>
<P1>h. Failing to advise Ashraf to amend his Statement of Claim while the pleadings were still open, which would have forestalled the Defendant's application for dismissal of the claim;</P1>
<P1>i. Failing to advice Ashraf to start a new action for constructive dismissal and seek damages arising from manner of dismissal;</P1>
<P1>j. Charging Ashraf for work not performed, or not performed competently; and taking him to a taxation when Ashraf questioned the account;</P1>
<P1>k. Accepting with an apology for his inefficient work, an amount in full satisfaction of his invoices but later upon his termination reneged the agreement and reclaimed full amount of his invoices for work not performed, reworks or not performed competently; and taking him to a taxation;</P1>
<P1>l. Breach of trust by repeatedly breaking of promises, contradictions in his operation and lack of transparency,</P1>
<P1>m. Failure to actively keep Ashraf up to date on the litigation process,</P1></P>
<P>216. It is respectfully submitted that Zinner is liable for damages arising from the breaches of his fiduciary duties.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V. CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>217. This case is not just about a lawyer's error in judgment or procedural slip. Zinner held himself out as an experienced litigator and employment lawyer, with 30 years of experience and with an hourly rate to match. Yet, he failed to advise his client that his entire claim would have been barred by virtue of the widely-known statutory immunity afforded to employers under the <EM>WCA</EM>.</P>
<P>218. Once he had been made aware of this serious mistake, Zinner ought to have, at a minimum, informed Ashraf of the procedural options available to salvage his claim. He did not. Worse yet, despite the fact that a summary judgment application was imminent, Zinner dragged his feet and ultimately gave up on Ashraf's case without informing him of his disinterest in the case and intention to virtually withdraw.</P>
<P>219. It is reasonably foreseeable that, as a litigation lawyer, leaving your client to sort out your errors on his own will inflict mental and physical stress upon him.</P>
<P>220. After his dealings with the Defendants, many lawyers either refused to take on the case because of stain and stigma attached to the action or they wanted far higher fees compared to an action properly started. On the other hand, Ashraf was financially and emotionally incapable of entrusting the SNC Action to any other lawyer on full retainer. The resulting damages were reasonably foreseeable, direct consequences of the Defendants' breaches. As such, the Defendants are liable to compensate Ashraf for all damages caused to him in the SNC action until and including its resolution in November 2017, the damages in the within actions (1401-03230 &amp; 1201-15851), the damages arising from years of suffering he endured as a result of Zinner's inadequate legal services and failure to act in a candid and loyal manner the impact of which continued all the way to the present day and will continue in future.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART VI. NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>221. Ashraf seeks the following relief:
<P1>a. A declaration that the Defendants breached their contractual, tortious and fiduciary duties to Ashraf;</P1>
<P1>b. An Order that the trial of this matter continue to determine the damages payable to Ashraf;</P1>
<P1>c. Costs of this Application; and</P1>
<P1>d. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems appropriate.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTIVELY SUBMITTED, this 15 day of March 2019.</P>
<P>Per: &ellip35;</P>
<P>SHIDAN ASHRAF</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
